description.narrative: Government and other service providers (non-governmental agencies) have enhanced capacities to provide child protection services which prevent and respond to violence and abuse, particularly in target countries., which contributes to Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice (Covid), Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, children in the Pacific are increasingly protected from violence and abuse.

description.narrative: The quality of child protection (CP) services is improving as a result of the five-week training of 41 social welfare officers from Fiji and Vanuatu on CP social work, and technical assistance in seven countries. Fiji, Kiribati, the Republic of the Marshall Islands (RMI), Solomon Islands, and Tuvalu made progress on their CP in schools policy/plan. Fiji, Kiribati, Samoa, and Tonga started integrating CP into health policies, plans, trainings, and/or protocols. Fiji and Kiribati strengthened police and court procedures related to children. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:03/02/2022
